[[File:Hank Chien.jpg|thumb|Hank Chien at the Kong Off 3 tournament in Denver, Colorado, in November 2013]]
The 2007 documentary ''[[The King of Kong: A Fistful of Quarters]]'' portrays [[Steve Wiebe]]'s attempts to break the ''Donkey Kong'' world record, then considered to have been held by [[Billy Mitchell (gamer)|Billy Mitchell]].<ref name="King of Kong, overview at AllMovie" /> In the early 2010s, [[Hank Chien]] set a record of 1,138,600 points. This was broken four years later by [[Robbie Lakeman]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Good |first=Owen S. |date=September 6, 2014 |title=Newcomer Sets All-Time High Score in Donkey Kong |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/9/6/6114647/donkey-kong-all-time-high-score-robbie-lakeman-hank-chien-steve-wiebe-billy-mitchell |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226201914/http://www.polygon.com/2014/9/6/6114647/donkey-kong-all-time-high-score-robbie-lakeman-hank-chien-steve-wiebe-billy-mitchell |archive-date=December 26, 2016 |access-date=December 24, 2016 |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> Lakeman's record was then broken by John McCurdy on January 11, 2021, with a score of 1,272,700.<ref name="mccurdy2021">{{Cite web |title=John McCurdy Gets 1,272,700 for a New Donkey Kong World Record!! |url=http://donkeykongforum.com/index.php?topic=2827 |access-date=January 13, 2021 |website=DonkeyKongForum.com}}</ref> Lakeman reclaimed the world record only five months later on June 8, scoring 100 more points than McCurdy.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Twin Galaxies Arcade - Donkey Kong - Points [Hammer Allowed] - 1,272,800 - Robbie Lakeman |url=https://www.twingalaxies.com/showthread.php/232686 |access-date=2021-08-06 |website=[[Twin Galaxies]] |language=en}}</ref>

In 2018, Mitchell was stripped of his records by [[Twin Galaxies]] and banned from submitting new scores after Twin Galaxies concluded that Mitchell had illicitly used [[video game emulator|emulator]]s to achieve his scores.<ref name="variety18">{{Cite web |last=Crecente |first=Brian |date=April 12, 2018 |title='King of Kong' Star Stripped of High Scores, Banned From Competition |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/king-of-kong-stripped-of-title-1202751358/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531013515/https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/king-of-kong-stripped-of-title-1202751358/ |archive-date=May 31, 2019 |access-date=November 25, 2018 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]}}</ref> Twin Galaxies prohibits the use of emulators for high scores they publish because they allow undetectable cheating.<ref name=variety18/> In 2020 ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' reversed its decision and reinstated Billy Mitchell's previous world records, based on new evidence including eyewitness reports and expert testimonials.<ref name="Mitchell Reinstatement">{{Cite web |date=2020-06-17 |title=A Statement from Guinness World Records: Billy Mitchell |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2020/6/a-statement-from-guinness-world-records-billy-mitchell-621053 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200619042823/https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2020/6/a-statement-from-guinness-world-records-billy-mitchell-621053 |archive-date=June 19, 2020 |access-date=2020-06-17 |website=[[Guinness World Records]] |df=mdy-all}}</ref>

There are other world record categories for ''Donkey Kong'' besides highest score. One of the most popular is the "No Hammer Challenge" where competitors try to get the highest score without using the hammer.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=Donkey Kong No Hammer Challenge |url=https://www.twingalaxies.com/game/donkey-kong/arcade/points-no-hammer-challenge/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221181751/http://www.twingalaxies.com:80/game/donkey-kong/arcade/points-no-hammer-challenge |archive-date=February 21, 2018 |access-date=2021-08-06 |website=[[Twin Galaxies]]}}</ref> The current world record in this category was set by Jeff Wolfe on July 8, 2008, with a score of 735,100.<ref name=":0" /> Some other categories include most points for different levels, and fewest points.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Donkey Kong Arcade World Record Categories |url=https://www.twingalaxies.com/game/donkey-kong |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200517083513/https://www.twingalaxies.com/game/donkey-kong |archive-date=May 17, 2020 |access-date=2021-08-06 |website=[[Twin Galaxies]]}}</ref>

==Plot==
{{Anchor|Story and characters}}
[[File:Dkong end.png|thumb|right|upright=1|On the final screen of each level, Mario and Pauline are reunited.]]
''Donkey Kong'' is considered to be the earliest video game with a storyline that visually unfolds on screen.<ref name="GamesRadar" /> Set on a [[construction site]] in [[New York City]],<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 25, 2023 |script-title=ja:マリオ映画公開記念！宮本茂さんインタビュー 制作の始まりから驚きの設定まで |trans-title=Commemorating the release of the Mario movie! Interview with Shigeru Miyamoto From the beginning of production to the surprising setting |url=https://www.ndw.jp/mario-interview-230425/2/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230425155151/https://www.ndw.jp/mario-interview-230425/2/ |archive-date=April 25, 2023 |website=[[Nintendo Dream]] |language=japanese |quote=もともと『マリオブラザーズ』は、土管がいっぱいあるニューヨークの地下で活躍する兄弟、ニューヨークのなかでもたぶんブルックリン、というところまで勝手に決めていて。『ドンキーコング』は舞台がニューヨークですし。その土管が不思議な森（キノコ王国）につながったのが、『スーパーマリオブラザーズ』なんです。['''Miyamoto:''' Originally, ''Mario Bros.'' was arbitrarily decided as brothers who are active in the underground of New York, where there are many clay pipes, and probably Brooklyn in New York. ''Donkey Kong'' is set in New York.  That clay pipe led to the mysterious forest (Mushroom Kingdom), which is ''Super Mario Bros.'']}}</ref> the eponymous Donkey Kong character is the game's ''[[de facto]]'' villain. The hero is a carpenter originally unnamed in the Japanese arcade release, later named Jumpman and then Mario.<ref name="History of SMB at IGN">{{Cite web |last=McLaughlin |first=Rus |date=September 14, 2010 |title=IGN Presents The History of Super Mario Bros. |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/09/14/ign-presents-the-history-of-super-mario-bros |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412223956/http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/09/14/ign-presents-the-history-of-super-mario-bros |archive-date=April 12, 2014 |access-date=April 9, 2014 |website=IGN}}</ref> Donkey Kong kidnaps Mario's girlfriend, originally known as Lady and later renamed Pauline. The player must take the role of Mario and rescue her. This is the first occurrence of the [[damsel in distress]] scenario that provided the template for countless video games released after.<ref name="High Score!" />{{rp|82}}

The game uses graphics and animation for characterization. Donkey Kong smirks upon Mario's demise. Pauline has a pink dress and long hair,<ref name="Gender Inclusive" />{{rp|19–20}} and a speech balloon crying "HELP!". Mario, depicted in red overalls and a red cap, is an [[everyman]] character, a type common in Japan. Graphical limitations and the low pixel resolution of the small [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] prompted his design. A mustache implies a mouth,<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|37}} a cap obviates the animation of hair, and colored overalls distinguish his arm movements.<ref name="High Score!" />{{rp|238}} The artwork of the cabinets and promotional materials make these cartoon-like character designs even more explicit. Pauline, for example, is depicted as disheveled like the 1930s ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]''{{'}}s [[Fay Wray]] in a torn dress and [[stiletto heel]]s.<ref name="Gender Inclusive" />{{rp|19–20}}

Like ''[[Pac-Man]]'' (1980), ''Donkey Kong'' has [[cutscene]]s, but innovates by advancing a complete plot.<ref name="Lebowitz">{{Cite book |last=Lebowitz |first=Josiah |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QUrarEcvaO8C&pg=PA14 |title=Interactive Storytelling for Video Games: A Player-centered Approach to Creating Memorable Characters and Stories |last2=Klug |first2=Chris |date=2011 |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |isbn=978-0-240-81717-0 |page=14 |access-date=April 25, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210425124157/https://books.google.com/books?id=QUrarEcvaO8C&pg=PA14 |archive-date=April 25, 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> The game opens with the gorilla climbing a pair of ladders to the top of a construction site, accompanied by a variation on the [[Dragnet (theme music)|musical theme]] from ''[[Dragnet (franchise)|Dragnet]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Dragnet – Video Game Music Preservation Foundation Wiki |url=http://www.vgmpf.com/Wiki/index.php?title=Dragnet |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202190501/http://vgmpf.com/Wiki/index.php?title=Dragnet |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |access-date=2020-12-15 |website=VGMPF.com}}</ref> He drops Pauline and stomps his feet, warping the steel beams. He moves to his final perch and sneers. A melody plays, and the level starts. This brief animation sets the scene and adds background to the gameplay, a first for video games. At the stage, a heart appears between Mario and Pauline, but Donkey Kong grabs her and climbs higher, causing the heart to break. The narrative concludes when Mario reaches the end of the rivet stage. He and Pauline are reunited, and a short intermission plays.<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|40–42}}

==Development==
{{Further|Radar Scope}}
[[File:Donkey Kong arcade at the QuakeCon 2005.png|thumb|left|upright=1|Small model based on original arcade cabinet]]
[[Nintendo of America]] was founded in 1980 with minor success at importing its parent's arcade cabinets from Japan. In early 1981, its president [[Minoru Arakawa]] bet the small startup company on a major order of 3,000 ''[[Radar Scope]]''.<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|103–105}}<ref name="History of SMB at IGN" /> Its poor reception in America filled a warehouse with 2,000 unsold ''Radar Scope'' machines, so Arakawa requested that the parent company president [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]] send a conversion kit of new game software. Yamauchi polled the company's entire talent pool for fresh game design concepts to save the distressed startup.<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|106}}<ref name="History of SMB at IGN" /><ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|157}} This yielded [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]'s debut as lead game designer of his ''Donkey Kong'' concept, and Yamauchi appointed head engineer [[Gunpei Yokoi]] as project supervisor<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|158}} with a budget of {{US$|267000|1981|long=no|round=-3}} according to Miyamoto.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=June 1992 |title=Unlikely Hero Creates Games and Profits |url=https://archive.org/details/Leisure_Line_1992-06_Leisure_Allied_Industries_AU/page/n24 |magazine=Leisure Line |publisher=Leisure & Allied Industries |location=Australia |pages=25–6}}</ref>

[[Ikegami Tsushinki]] was subcontracted for some of the development, with no role in the game's creation or concept, but to provide "mechanical programming assistance to fix the software created by Nintendo".<ref name="cch85">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WVdsAAAAIAAJ |title=Copyright law decisions |publisher=[[CCH (Commerce Clearing House)|Commerce Clearing House]] |year=1985 |quote=An English translation of the Japanese term Donkey Kong is "crazy gorilla". Nintendo Co., Ltd. expended over $100,000.00 in direct development of the game, and Nintendo Co., Ltd. hired Ikegami Tsushinki Co., Ltd. to provide mechanical programming assistance to fix the software created by Nintendo Co., Ltd. in the storage component of the game. The name "Ikegami Co. Lim." appears in the computer program for the Donkey Kong game. Individuals within the research and development department of Nintendo Co., Ltd., however, created the Donkey Kong concept and game. |access-date=February 26, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710030942/https://books.google.com/books?id=WVdsAAAAIAAJ |archive-date=July 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Fahs |first=Travis |date=2011-07-06 |title=The Secret History of Donkey Kong |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/6422/the_secret_history_of_donkey_kong.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819101333/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/6422/the_secret_history_of_donkey_kong.php |archive-date=2011-08-19 |access-date=2023-01-15 |website=[[Gamasutra]]}}</ref> Nintendo instructed Ikegami to produce a program according to its instructions and put it onto [[read-only memory]] (ROM) chips on [[printed circuit boards]] (PC boards). This later led to mutual lawsuits in 1983, as Ikegami asserted ownership over ''Donkey Kong'' which Nintendo denied as Ikegami was a subcontractor who had already been paid. ''[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]]'' called it "simply a nuisance tactic" on the part of Ikegami.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=1 September 1983 |title=Overseas Readers Column: Nintendo and Ikegami Sue Each Other On The Copyright Of Nintendo's "Donkey Kong" |url=https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19830901p.pdf#page=16 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210410033338/https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19830901p.pdf#page=16 |archive-date=April 10, 2021 |access-date=May 20, 2021 |magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]] |publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]] |page=30 |issue=219 |lang=ja}}</ref>

At the time, Nintendo was also pursuing a license to make a game based on the ''[[Popeye]]'' comic strip. When they experienced technical issues, Nintendo took the opportunity to create new characters that could be marketed and used in later games.<ref>[[Universal City Studios, Inc. v. Nintendo Co., Ltd.]]</ref> Miyamoto came up with many characters and plot concepts, but he settled on a love triangle between a gorilla, a plumber with a large hammer, and a girlfriend, mirroring the rivalry between [[Bluto]] and Popeye for [[Olive Oyl]].<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|39}} Bluto became an ape, which Miyamoto said was "nothing too evil or repulsive".<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|47}} He would be the pet of the main character, "a funny, hang-loose kind of guy".<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|47}} Miyamoto has named "[[Beauty and the Beast]]" and the 1933 film ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]'' as influences.<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|36}} Although its origin as a comic strip license played a major part, ''Donkey Kong'' marked the first time that the storyline for a video game preceded the game's [[computer programming|programming]] rather than simply being appended as an afterthought.<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|38}} An unrelated Popeye game was released by Nintendo for the [[Game & Watch]] the following month, as well as a game called ''[[Popeye (video game)|Popeye]]'' for arcades in 1982.

Yamauchi wanted primarily to target the North American market, so he mandated that the game be given an English title, as with many previous Nintendo games. Miyamoto decided to name the game for the ape, who he said was the strongest character.<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|39}} The story of how Miyamoto came up with the name "Donkey Kong" varies. A false urban myth says that the name was originally meant to be "Monkey Kong", but was misspelled or misinterpreted due to a blurred fax or bad telephone connection.<ref name="Donkey Wrong" /> Another, more credible story claims Miyamoto looked in a Japanese-English dictionary for something that would mean "stubborn gorilla",<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|158}} or that "Donkey" was meant to convey "silly" or "stubborn"; "Kong" was common Japanese slang for "gorilla".<ref name="High Score!" />{{rp|238}} A rival claim is that he worked with Nintendo's export manager to come up with the title, and that "Donkey" was meant to represent "stupid and goofy".<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|48–49}} In 2001, Miyamoto stated that he thought the name would convey the thought of a "stupid ape".<ref name="miyamotoshrine">{{Cite web |title=Miyamoto Shrine: Shigeru Miyamoto's Home on The Web |url=http://www.miyamotoshrine.com/theman/interviews/051601.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702082511/http://www.miyamotoshrine.com/theman/interviews/051601.shtml |archive-date=July 2, 2007 |access-date=May 31, 2007 |website=Interview with Miyamoto (May 16, 2001, E3 Expo)}}</ref>

Miyamoto had high hopes for his new project. He was not a programmer, so instead consulted technicians for concept feasibility. He wanted to make the characters different sizes, and have different movements and reactions. Yokoi thought Miyamoto's original design was too complex,<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|47–48}} though he had some difficult suggestions, such as using see-saws to catapult the hero across the screen which was eventually found too hard to program, though a similar concept came later in the ''Popeye'' arcade game. Miyamoto then thought of using sloped platforms, barrels, and ladders. When he specified that the game would have multiple stages, the four-man programming team complained that he was essentially asking them to implement the game repeatedly.<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|38–39}} Nevertheless, they followed Miyamoto's design, creating a total of approximately 20 [[Kibibyte|kilobytes]] of content.<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|530}} Yukio Kaneoka composed a soundtrack to serve as background music for the levels and story events.<ref name="famicom20th">{{Cite AV media notes |title=Famicom 20th Anniversary Original Sound Tracks Vol. 1 |url=http://vgmdb.net/album/404 |year=2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202033612/http://vgmdb.net/album/404 |publisher=Scitron Digital Contents Inc. |archive-date=December 2, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="music">{{Cite web |title=Donkey Kong |url=http://www.smashbros.com/en_us/music/music15.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312011921/http://www.smashbros.com/en_us/music/music15.html |archive-date=March 12, 2008 |access-date=March 8, 2008 |website=Smash Bros. DOJO!! |df=mdy-all}}</ref>

The circuit board of ''Radar Scope'' was restructured for ''Donkey Kong''. The ''Radar Scope'' hardware, originally inspired by the [[Namco]] ''[[Namco Galaxian|Galaxian]]'' hardware, was designed for a large number of enemies moving around at high speeds, which ''Donkey Kong'' does not require, so the development team removed unnecessary functions and reduced the scale of the circuit board.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120505103737/http://www.glitterberri.com/developer-interviews/how-the-famicom-was-born/making-the-famicom-a-reality/ Making the Famicom a Reality], ''Nikkei Electronics'' (September 12, 1994) (translation by Nathan Altice)</ref> The gameplay and graphics were reworked for updated [[Read-only memory|ROM]] chips, and the existing [[Central processing unit|CPU]], sound hardware, and monitor were left intact.<ref>Nathan Altice (2015), [https://books.google.com/books?id=GVDpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA55 ''I Am Error: The Nintendo Family Computer / Entertainment System Platform'', page 55] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217204830/https://books.google.com/books?id=GVDpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA55 |date=February 17, 2017}}, [[MIT Press]]</ref> The character set, scoreboard, upper HUD display, and font are almost identical to ''Radar Scope'', with palette differences.<ref>Nathan Altice (2015), [https://books.google.com/books?id=GVDpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA362 ''I Am Error: The Nintendo Family Computer / Entertainment System Platform'', page 362] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217141022/https://books.google.com/books?id=GVDpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA362 |date=February 17, 2017}}, [[MIT Press]]</ref> The ''Donkey Kong'' hardware has the memory capacity for displaying 128 foreground [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] at 16x16 [[pixel]]s each and 256 background [[Tile-based video game|tiles]] at 8x8 pixels each. Mario and all moving objects use single sprites, the taller Pauline uses two sprites, and the larger Donkey Kong uses six sprites.<ref>Nathan Altice (2015), [https://books.google.com/books?id=GVDpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA69 ''I Am Error: The Nintendo Family Computer / Entertainment System Platform'', page 69] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217205141/https://books.google.com/books?id=GVDpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA69 |date=February 17, 2017}}, [[MIT Press]]</ref>

Hiroshi Yamauchi thought the game was going to sell well and phoned to inform Arakawa. Nintendo of America's distributors, Ron Judy and Al Stone, brought Arakawa to the lawyer [[Howard Lincoln]] to secure a trademark.<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|159}}

The game was sent to Nintendo of America for testing. The sales manager disliked it for being too different from the [[maze game|maze]] and [[shooter game]]s common at the time,<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|49}} and Judy and Lincoln expressed reservations over the strange title. Still, Arakawa adamantly believed that it would be a hit.<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|159}} American staff began translating the storyline for the cabinet art and naming the characters. They chose "Pauline" for the Lady, after Polly James, wife of Nintendo's warehouse manager [[Don James (executive)|Don James]].<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|200}} Arakawa suggested that the name of "Jumpman", a name originally chosen for its similarity to the popular brands [[Walkman]] and ''[[Pac-Man]]'',<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|34–42}} be changed to "Mario" in likeness of [[Mario Segale]], the landlord of the original office space of Nintendo of America.<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|42}}<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|109}} These character names were used in promotional materials, although Mario was called Jumpman in the operations manual and instructions.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Donkey Kong Operation Manual |url=https://www.arcade-museum.com/manuals-videogames/D/dk-tkg4u.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210323233657/https://www.sis.gov.eg/Story/67988/Media-Production-City?lang=en-us |archive-date=March 23, 2021 |website=The International Game Museum}}</ref> ''Donkey Kong'' was ready for release.<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|212}}

Stone and Judy convinced the managers of two bars in Seattle, Washington, to set up ''Donkey Kong'' machines. The managers initially showed reluctance, but when they saw sales of $30 a day—or 120 plays—for a solid week, they requested more units.<ref name="Arcade Fever" />{{rp|68}} In their Redmond headquarters, a skeleton crew composed of Arakawa, his wife Yoko, James, Judy, Phillips, and Stone gutted 2,000 surplus ''Radar Scope'' machines and applied the ''Donkey Kong'' conversion kits imported from Japan, consisting of [[motherboard]]s, power supplies, and marquee graphics.<ref name="History of SMB at IGN" /><ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|110}} The game officially went on sale in July 1981.<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|211}}

