=== Coleco ===
Makers of [[video game console]]s were interested. [[Taito]] offered a considerable fee for all rights to ''Donkey Kong'', but Nintendo declined after three days of internal discussion.<ref name="Game Over" /> Rivals [[Coleco]] and [[Atari, Inc.]] approached Nintendo in Japan and the United States respectively. In the end, Yamauchi granted Coleco exclusive console and [[tabletop game|tabletop]] rights to ''Donkey Kong'' because he believed that "it [was] the hungriest company".<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|111}} In addition, Arakawa believed that as a more established company in the U.S., Coleco could better handle marketing. In return, Nintendo received an undisclosed lump sum plus $1.40 per game cartridge sold and $1 per tabletop unit. On December 24, 1981, Howard Lincoln drafted the contract. He included language that Coleco would be held liable for anything on the game cartridge, an unusual clause for a licensing agreement.<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|208–209}} Arakawa signed the document the next day, and, on February 1, 1982, Yamauchi persuaded the Coleco representative in Japan to sign without review by the company's lawyers.<ref name="Game Over" />{{rp|112}}

Coleco bundled the game with the [[ColecoVision]] console, which went on sale in August 1982, though the individual cartridge was also available in stores. Coleco offered [[Atari 2600]] and [[Intellivision]] versions as well.<ref name="arcexp">{{Cite magazine |date=August 30, 1982 |title=Coleco Rolls Videogame Line |url=https://archive.org/details/arcade_express_v1n2 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926002449/https://archive.org/details/arcade_express_v1n2 |archive-date=September 26, 2016 |magazine=Arcade Express |page=3 |volume=1 |issue=2}}</ref> Coleco's Atari 2600 port was programmed by [[Garry Kitchen]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=24 March 2014 |title=Garry Kitchen |url=https://www.retrogamer.net/profiles/developer/garry-kitchen/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120174116/https://www.retrogamer.net/profiles/developer/garry-kitchen/ |archive-date=January 20, 2021 |access-date=19 April 2021 |website=[[Retro Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future Publishing]]}}</ref><ref name=BeforeYouDie/>{{rp|35}} Kitchen was contracted to port the game through his brother Steve, who had connections to an executive at Coleco. He was given only three or four months to develop the port and worked without sleep for the last 72 hours before shipping. Kitchen received no assistance from Nintendo and minimal aid from Coleco, who only provided him with an arcade machine for temporary use. These factors combined with the limited memory of Atari 2600 cartridges forced him to omit two of the original game's four levels.<ref name=BeforeYouDie/>{{rp|35}} Coleco's sales subsequently doubled to $500 million and its earnings quadrupled to $40 million.<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|210}} Coleco also released stand-alone [[Coleco#History|Mini-Arcade]] tabletop versions of ''Donkey Kong'', along with ''[[Pac-Man]]'', ''[[Galaxian]]'', and ''[[Frogger]]'' in 1982.<ref name="eg_16_10">{{Cite magazine |date=June 1983 |title=More Mini-Arcades A Comin' |url=https://archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1983-06/Electronic_Games_Issue_16_Vol_02_04_1983_Jun#page/n9/mode/2up |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122041852/http://www.archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1983-06/Electronic_Games_Issue_16_Vol_02_04_1983_Jun |archive-date=January 22, 2013 |access-date=February 1, 2012 |magazine=[[Electronic Games]] |page=10 |volume=4 |issue=16}}</ref><ref name="arcexp1_1">{{Cite magazine |date=August 15, 1982 |title=Coleco Mini-arcades G Gold |url=https://archive.org/details/arcade_express_v1n1 |magazine=Arcade Express |page=4 |volume=1 |issue=1}}</ref> Coleco also bundled a copy of ''Donkey Kong'' with its Atari VCS clone, the [[Coleco Gemini]], in 1983.<ref>{{Cite book |title=1982 Annual Report |date=April 8, 1983 |publisher=Coleco |page=17}}</ref>

=== Atari ===
Atari obtained the license for [[home computer]] versions of ''Donkey Kong''<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=11 December 1982 |title=Atari, Nintendo Pact For Home Computer Version of 'Donkey Kong' |url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox44unse_26/page/35 |magazine=[[Cash Box]] |publisher=Cash Box Pub. Co. |pages=35–6}}</ref> and released it for the [[Atari 8-bit computers]]. When Coleco unveiled the [[Coleco Adam|Adam Computer]], running a port of ''Donkey Kong'' at the 1983 [[Consumer Electronics Show]] in Chicago, Illinois, Atari protested that it was in violation of the licensing agreement. Yamauchi demanded that [[Arnold Greenberg (Coleco)|Arnold Greenberg]], Coleco's president, withdraw his Adam port. Greenberg complied, and the game was not published.<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|283–285}}

The [[Atari 8-bit]] conversion of ''Donkey Kong'' contains one of the longest-undiscovered ''[[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]]'' in a video game.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 4, 2009 |title=Donkey Kong Easter Egg Discovered 26 Years Later |url=http://kotaku.com/5307375/donkey-kong-easter-egg-discovered-26-years-later/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603135127/http://kotaku.com/5307375/donkey-kong-easter-egg-discovered-26-years-later |archive-date=June 3, 2013 |access-date=May 29, 2013 |publisher=Kotaku.com}}</ref> Programmer Landon Dyer's initials appear if the player dies under certain conditions and returns to the title screen. This remained undiscovered for 26 years until Dyer revealed it on his blog, stating that "there's an Easter egg, but it's totally not worth it, and I don't remember how to bring it up anyway".<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 4, 2008 |title=Donkey Kong and Me |url=http://www.dadhacker.com/blog/?p=987/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603232605/http://www.dadhacker.com/blog/?p=987/ |archive-date=June 3, 2013 |access-date=May 29, 2013 |publisher=Dadhacker.com}}</ref> The steps required to trigger it were later discovered by Don Hodges, who used an emulator and a debugger to trace through the game's code.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hodges |first=Don |date=July 1, 2009 |title=Donkey Kong Lays an Easter Egg |url=http://donhodges.com/donkey_kong_easter_egg.htm |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906134639/http://donhodges.com/donkey_kong_easter_egg.htm |archive-date=September 6, 2011}}</ref>

===Famicom/NES===
{{Further|History of the Nintendo Entertainment System}}
The game was ported by [[Nintendo Research & Development 2]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=Iwata |first=Satoru |title=Iwata Asks: New Super Mario Bros: Volume 2: It All Began In 1984 |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wii/nsmb/1/0 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816051935/http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wii/nsmb/1/0 |archive-date=August 16, 2013 |access-date=2019-01-25 |website=iwataasks.nintendo.com |quote=I worked on a wide variety of titles together with R&D2, including Donkey Kong5, which was released at the same time as the Famicom}}</ref> to Nintendo's [[Family Computer]] (Famicom) console and released in Japan on July 15, 1983, as one of the system's three [[launch game]]s.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Marley |first=Scott |date=December 2016 |title=SG-1000 |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future Publishing]] |pages=56–61 |issue=163}}</ref> [[Masayuki Uemura]], the Famicom's lead architect, designed the console specifically to faithfully recreate ''Donkey Kong''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Volume 2: NES & Mario |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wii/mario25th/1/1 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816051935/http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wii/mario25th/1/1 |archive-date=August 16, 2013 |access-date=May 2, 2021 |website=[[Iwata Asks]] |publisher=Nintendo |page=2. Playing Donkey Kong at Home}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Parish |first=Jeremy |date=December 11, 2018 |title=NES Creator Masayuki Uemura on the Birth of Nintendo's First Console |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/nes-creator-masayuki-uemura-on-the-birth-of-nintendos-first-console/page-2 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503045549/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/nes-creator-masayuki-uemura-on-the-birth-of-nintendos-first-console/page-2 |archive-date=May 3, 2021 |access-date=May 2, 2021 |website=[[USgamer]] |page=2}}</ref> It is an early [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] (NES) game in the ''Arcade Classics Series'', released on June 1, 1986, in North America and October 15 in Europe. Omitted are the cement factory stage and most of the cutscenes, because early ROM cartridges do not have enough memory. It includes a new song composed by Yukio Kaneoka for the title screen.<ref name="famicom20th" /> Both ''Donkey Kong'' and its sequel, ''[[Donkey Kong Jr.]]'', are included in the 1988 NES compilation ''Donkey Kong Classics''.

===Game Boy===
{{Main|Donkey Kong (1994 video game)|l1 = ''Donkey Kong'' (1994 video game)}}

A complete remake of the original arcade game on the [[Game Boy]], titled ''[[Donkey Kong (1994 video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' (referred to as ''Donkey Kong '94'' during development) contains levels from both the original ''Donkey Kong'' and ''Donkey Kong Jr.'' arcades. It starts with the same gameplay and four locations as the arcade game and then progresses to 97 additional puzzle-based levels. It is the first game to have built-in enhancement for the [[Super Game Boy]] system.{{cn|date=July 2022}}

