rossing [[1982 in video games|arcade game of 1982]].<ref name="RePlay">{{Cite magazine |date=March 1987 |title=Top Hits of Last 5 Years |magazine=RePlay}}</ref> It was also among the thirteen highest-grossing [[1983 in video games|arcade games of 1983]] in the United States.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=October 29, 1983 |title=AMOA Votes On Annual Game Awards |url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox45unse_20/page/68 |magazine=[[Cash Box]] |page=60}}</ref> According to ''[[Electronic Games]]'' in June 1983, the home versions contributed to the arcade version's extended popularity, compared to the four to six months that the average game lasted.<ref name="pearl198306">{{Cite news |last=Pearl, Rick |date=June 1983 |title=Closet Classics |url=https://archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1983-06/Electronic_Games_Issue_16_Vol_02_04_1983_Jun#page/n79/mode/2up |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107032556/http://www.archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1983-06/Electronic_Games_Issue_16_Vol_02_04_1983_Jun |archive-date=January 7, 2015 |access-date=January 6, 2015 |work=Electronic Games |page=82}}</ref> It remained Nintendo's top seller into mid-1983,<ref name="Ultimate History" />{{rp|284}} with steady sales in Japan.<ref name="Power-up" />{{rp|46}} A total of 65,000 arcade units were sold in Japan,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Ashcraft |first=Brian |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wX8kAQAAIAAJ |title=Arcade Mania: The Turbo-charged World of Japan's Game Centers |last2=Snow |first2=Jean |publisher=[[Kodansha]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-4-7700-3078-8 |edition=1st |location=Tokyo |quote=Jumpman hopped over barrels, climbed ladders, and jumped from suspended platform to suspended platform as he tried to rescue a damsel from his pissed-off pet gorilla. The game was a smash, and sixty-five thousand cabinets were sold in Japan, propping up the then-struggling Nintendo and laying the groundwork for Nintendo and ''Donkey Kong'' creator Shigeru Miyamoto to dominate gaming throughout the 1980s and beyond. |access-date=March 3, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210225054458/https://books.google.com/books?id=wX8kAQAAIAAJ |archive-date=February 25, 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> and 67,000 arcade units in the United States,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bienaimé |first=Pierre |date=13 January 2012 |title=Square Roots: Donkey Kong (NES) |url=http://www.nintendojo.com/features/columns/square-roots/square-roots-donkey-kong-nes |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201042701/http://www.nintendojo.com/features/columns/square-roots/square-roots-donkey-kong-nes |archive-date=1 February 2012 |publisher=Nintendojo |quote=Donkey Kong sold some 67,000 arcade cabinets in two years, making two of its American distributors sudden millionaires thanks to paid commission. As a barometer of success, know that Pac-Man and Ms. Pac-Man are the only arcade games to have sold over 100,000 units in the United States.}}</ref> for a total of {{formatnum:{{#expr:65000+67000}}|}} arcade units sold in Japan and the United States.

